<h2 id="becoming-children-of-god">Becoming Children of God</h2>

<p>Those who believed in his name <em>were given</em> the <em>right</em> to become children of God.</p>

<p>A few points here:</p>
<ul>
<li>This was bestowed upon them, not taken by them, or possibly even chosen by them</li>
<li>This is a <em>right</em>, a guaranteed action</li>
<li>They became children of God, not remaining just a mere creation of him</li>
</ul>

<p>So, although this is a right of these people, it is only because Jesus gives them this right.  Being a right, this is something we can put our trust and hope upon.  Itâ€™s a guarantee (See Eph 1:13, 14).</p>

<p>Being a child of God is not the same as being a creation of God.  Itâ€™s a different status and a different relationship.  I suppose this is a bit like Pinnochio and Geppetto.  Pinnochio was a creation, but he became a son.  Geppetto created a lot of puppets, but this one had a real relationship with him.  Furthermore, this was the relationship of a father and child, not a boss and employee, not even a stepfather/stepson relationship.</p>

<p>It would be interesting to see how revolutionary this idea of â€œGod as Fatherâ€ was at the time.  Was God portrayed as a father very often in the Old Testament?  If so, did it reflect the importance of this role as Jesus portrayed it?</p>

<p>This birth (v13) was not a literal hereditary one (by blood), nor of the desire by our humanity (will of the flesh), nor of the work or trying by these humans (will [desire] of man), but of God.</p>

<p>To cut out any cruft, â€œThis birth was <em>of</em> God.â€  Thatâ€™s an interesting concept.  The idea of fleshly or human will is completely removed from this birth.  This birth had nothing to do with our bodies, desires, or work.  It was done by God.  Note that this birth completely disregards manâ€™s will.</p>

